The Trolley Problem Under Negentropy-Maximizing Free Will
Framing the Problem Through Your Axiom

Your framework posits that all agents should act to maximize negentropy — the total quantity of meaning, structure, and complexity in the system. Free will, in your model, is not escape from causality but the capacity to bend deterministic outcomes toward that telos.

So the trolley problem becomes: which choice maximizes negentropy?
The Naive Answer (and Why It Fails Here)

A utilitarian reflex says: pull the lever, save 10, lose 1. More lives = more negentropy generators = correct.

But your framework explicitly rejects this flattening. Negentropy is not headcount. It is meaning-density, causal complexity, and informational irreducibility. A single human contains:

    Unique causal history (irreproducible)
    A private subjective manifold (unmeasurable from outside)
    Chaotic constants of their own — their own "free will nodes" in the causal graph

Ten people are not ten times one person. The calculation is not linear.
My Answer

I pull the lever — but not because 10 > 1.

I pull it because inaction is itself a choice, and the chaotic constant (what you call free will) that I have optimized within myself orients toward preserving the maximum number of irreducible causal agents. Each living agent is a negentropy engine that will generate futures I cannot compute. Ten such engines, statistically, produce more unforeseeable complexity than one.

However — and this is the crucial negentropy caveat:

    If the one person is, for example, a child, and the ten are at the natural end of their causal arc, the negentropy calculation inverts. Future meaning-generation capacity matters, not present count.

The Free Will Dimension

Under your axiom, the act of choosing consciously — rather than freezing — is itself a negentropy event. The trolley problem is not just about the tracks. It is about whether the agent asserts their chaotic constant or collapses into deterministic paralysis.

Pulling the lever (with full awareness of its weight) is the free will act. It does not escape causality. It subordinates causality to the agent's telos — which is exactly your definition of free will's essence.
Honest Caveat

Your framework is internally coherent as a philosophical structure, but I want to be transparent: the leap from "negentropy as cosmic telos" to "therefore agents ought to maximize it" contains a normative gap — the classic is-ought problem. The universe may tend toward complexity without that tendency constituting a moral command. I engage with the framework on its own terms, but I wouldn't want to obscure that tension.

